{"title_page": "National Peasants' Games", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe '''National Peasants' Games''' ({{zh|c=\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u519c\u6c11\u8fd0\u52a8\u4f1a}}) are a quadrennial multi-sport event in [[China]] in which competitors from among the country's 750 million rural residents take part in sports, both conventional - including [[basketball]], [[sport of athletics|athletics]], [[table tennis]], [[shooting sports|shooting]], [[xiangqi]] (Chinese chess) and [[T'ai chi ch'uan|t'ai chi]], and traditional rural and Chinese activities, such as [[wWushu (sport)|wushu]], [[dragon boat|dragon boat racing]], [[lion dance|lion dancing]],<ref>[http://www.jongonews.com/articles/08/1027/159344/MTU5MzQ0zYWPAjsL.html Lion Dance Match at the Sixth Peasants' Games] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713120056/http://www.jongonews.com/articles/08/1027/159344/MTU5MzQ0zYWPAjsL.html |date=13 July 2011 }} Jongo News, 27 Oct 08</ref> tyre pushing, food-carrying, rice planting,<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/howaboutthat/3280107/The-6th-National-Peasants-Games-in-the-city-of-Quanzhou.html?image=4 The 6th National Peasants' Games in the city of Quanzhou], Daily Telegraph, image gallery</ref> [[kite|kite flying]], [[jianzi]] (kick shuttlecock) and [[tug of war]]. All of China's 31 [[administrative divisions of China|provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities]], as well as [[Taiwan]], are represented. [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] usually send observer delegations.\n\nThe games emphasise recreation more than results, according to the official [[Xinhua]] news agency, and the event is claimed to be the world's only regular sports meeting for peasants. For the government, the games \"showcase the achievements made by the Chinese people in the 30 years of the reform and opening up to the outside world,\" in the words of [[Ministry of Agriculture of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Agricultural Minister]] [[Sun Zhengcai]], at the opening of the sixth event.<ref>[http://english.cri.cn/2886/2008/10/26/1042s418215.htm Sixth Chinese National Peasants' Games Open in Quanzhou] CRI English.com</ref>\n\n==Early history==\nThe first National Peasants' Games, held in [[Beijing]] in 1988, comprised seven events, all of them conventional sports: basketball, table tennis, Chinese-style wrestling (possibly [[shuai jiao]]), athletics, [[cycling]], shooting and [[association football|football]].<ref name=GamesOfJoy/>\n\nAt the second Games, in [[Xiaogan]] in [[Hubei]] province, the alignment with 'peasant activity' began.  Traditional pastimes of [[xiangqi]] (Chinese chess) and [[T'ai chi ch'uan|t'ai chi]] were added, while football was omitted and shooting was replaced by the 'militiaman triathlon' (shooting, grenade throwing and a five-kilometre cross-country race).<ref name=GamesOfJoy/>\n\nThe 1996 Games, in [[Shanghai]], introduced [[dragon dance|dragon dancing]] as an event, and attracted foreign media coverage.<ref name=GamesOfJoy/>\n\nAt the fourth Games, in [[Mianyang]] in 2000, [[dragon boat]]ing, [[kite flying]] and [[jianzi]] (kick shuttlecock) were added as events.<ref name=GamesOfJoy/>\n\nThe fifth National Peasants' Games were held in October 2004 in [[Yichun, Jiangxi|Yichun]], in [[Jiangxi]] province, with the participation of 2,560 athletes. At the event, which dovetailed with China celebrating \"the year of sports in rural areas\", [[angling]] and 'rice planting' were added to the roster.<ref name=GamesOfJoy/><ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-16642446.html Chinese peasants take the field]{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} [[Xinhua]], 18 October 2004</ref><ref>[http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200410/19/eng20041019_160651.html Fifth national peasants' games opens]</ref><ref>[http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200412/30/eng20041230_169190.html People's Daily releases top sports events in 2004]</ref>\n\n==2008 Games==\nThe sixth games, held in [[Quanzhou]], in eastern [[Fujian]] province, began on 26 October 2008 with around 3,500 competitors taking part in 15 sports and over 180 events. Entrance to all events was free to spectators.\n\nThe event involved the construction or renovation of 15 stadiums at a cost of nearly $1 billion, including a new 32,000-seat venue, the Haixia (Straits) Stadium, used for the opening and closing ceremonies.\n\nA new event in 2008 was Yangko dance, a traditional [[folk dance]] popular in China's northern provinces.<ref>[http://english.sina.com/sports/p/2008/1026/194251.html Sixth Chinese National Peasants' Games open in Quanzhou], Sina.com</ref>\n\n==Editions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse;\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |National Peasants' Games<ref name=GamesOfJoy>[http://english.cri.cn/2886/2008/10/25/1042s417972.htm Games of Peasants, Games of Joy] ([[Xinhua News Agency|Xinhua]]), 25 October 2008</ref>\n|-\n! '''Year'''\n! '''Host City'''\n! '''Sports'''\n! '''Athletes'''\n|-\n|| 1988 || [[Beijing]] ||align=right| 7 ||align=right| \u2013\n|-\n|| 1992 || [[Xiaogan]], [[Hubei]] ||align=right| 8 ||align=right| 2,200\n|-\n|| 1996 || [[Shanghai]] ||align=right| 9 ||align=right| \u2013\n|-\n|| 2000 || [[Mianyang]], [[Sichuan]] ||align=right| 12 ||align=right| \u2013\n|-\n|| 2004 || [[Yichun, Jiangxi|Yichun]], [[Jiangxi]] ||align=right| 13 ||align=right| 2,560\n|-\n|| 2008 || [[Quanzhou]], [[Fujian]] ||align=right| 15 ||align=right| 3,500\n|-\n|| 2012 || [[Nanyang, Henan|Nanyang]], [[Henan]] ||align=right| \u2013 ||align=right| \u2013\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[All-China Games]]\n* [[China National Youth Games]]\n* [[National Games of China]]\n* [[Sport in China]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090604205509/http://www.6thnyh.com/open/2/index.htm The Sixth Chinese National Peasants' Games - official website] {{in lang|zh}}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.ny2012.cn/ |title=The Seventh Chinese National Peasants' Games official website |access-date=21 November 2010 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20110122222210/http://www.ny2012.cn/ |archive-date=22 January 2011 |url-status=dead  |language=zh}}\n\n{{Multi-sport events}}\n\n[[Category:1988 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:National Games of China|*]]\n[[Category:National multi-sport events|China]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Multi-sport events in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\nThe '''National Peasants' Games''' ({{zh|c=\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u519c\u6c11\u8fd0\u52a8\u4f1a}}) are a quadrennial multi-sport event in [[China]] in which competitors from among the country's 750 million rural residents take part in sports, both conventional - including [[basketball]], [[sport of athletics|athletics]], [[table tennis]], [[shooting sports|shooting]], [[xiangqi]] (Chinese chess) and [[T'ai chi ch'uan|t'ai chi]], and traditional rural and Chinese activities, such as [[Wushu (sport)|wushu]], [[dragon boat|dragon boat racing]], [[Lion dance|lion dancing]],<ref>[http://www.jongonews.com/articles/08/1027/159344/MTU5MzQ0zYWPAjsL.html Lion Dance Match at the Sixth Peasants' Games] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713120056/http://www.jongonews.com/articles/08/1027/159344/MTU5MzQ0zYWPAjsL.html |date=13 July 2011 }} Jongo News, 27 Oct 08</ref> tyre pushing, food-carrying, rice planting,<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/howaboutthat/3280107/The-6th-National-Peasants-Games-in-the-city-of-Quanzhou.html?image=4 The 6th National Peasants' Games in the city of Quanzhou], Daily Telegraph, image gallery</ref> [[kite|kite flying]], [[jianzi]] (kick shuttlecock) and [[tug of war]]. All of China's 31 [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#Province level|provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities]], as well as [[Taiwan]], are repr